trans-unit.source: This topic describes the **bingmaps:**, **ms-drive-to:**, and **ms-walk-to:** Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes.
trans-unit.target: This topic describes the **bingmaps:**, **ms-drive-to:**, and **ms-walk-to:** Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes.

trans-unit.source: Use these URI schemes to launch the Windows Maps app to specific maps, directions, and search results.
trans-unit.target: Use these URI schemes to launch the Windows Maps app to specific maps, directions, and search results.

trans-unit.source: **Tip** To learn more about launching the Windows Maps app from your app, download the [Universal Windows Platform (UWP) map sample](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619977) from the [Windows-universal-samples repo](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619979) on GitHub.
trans-unit.target: **Tip** To learn more about launching the Windows Maps app from your app, download the [Universal Windows Platform (UWP) map sample](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619977) from the [Windows-universal-samples repo](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619979) on GitHub.

trans-unit.source: URI schemes let you open apps by clicking hyperlinks (or programmatically, in your app).
trans-unit.target: URI schemes let you open apps by clicking hyperlinks (or programmatically, in your app).

trans-unit.source: Just as you can start a new email using **mailto:** or open a web browser using **http:**, you can open the Windows maps app using **bingmaps:**, **ms-drive-to:**, and **ms-walk-to:**.
trans-unit.target: Just as you can start a new email using **mailto:** or open a web browser using **http:**, you can open the Windows maps app using **bingmaps:**, **ms-drive-to:**, and **ms-walk-to:**.

trans-unit.source: The **bingmaps:** URI provides maps for locations, search results, directions, and traffic.
trans-unit.target: The **bingmaps:** URI provides maps for locations, search results, directions, and traffic.

trans-unit.source: The **ms-drive-to:** URI provides turn-by-turn driving directions from your current location.
trans-unit.target: The **ms-drive-to:** URI provides turn-by-turn driving directions from your current location.

trans-unit.source: The **ms-walk-to:** URI provides turn-by-turn walking directions from your current location.
trans-unit.target: The **ms-walk-to:** URI provides turn-by-turn walking directions from your current location.

trans-unit.source: For example, the following URI opens the Windows Maps app and displays a map centered over New York City.
trans-unit.target: For example, the following URI opens the Windows Maps app and displays a map centered over New York City.

trans-unit.source: a map centered over new york city.
trans-unit.target: a map centered over new york city.

trans-unit.source: There are several ways to control the map center point and the zoom level.
trans-unit.target: There are several ways to control the map center point and the zoom level.

trans-unit.source: Using *cp* (center point) and *lvl* (zoom level) parameters are the most straightforward methods and they produce predictable results.
trans-unit.target: Using *cp* (center point) and *lvl* (zoom level) parameters are the most straightforward methods and they produce predictable results.

trans-unit.source: Using *bb* parameter (specifies an area bounded by latitude and longitude values) is less predictable because it takes into account the screen resolution and determines the map center point and zoom level based on the coordinates provided.
trans-unit.target: Using *bb* parameter (specifies an area bounded by latitude and longitude values) is less predictable because it takes into account the screen resolution and determines the map center point and zoom level based on the coordinates provided.

trans-unit.source: The *bb* parameter is ignored when all three parameters (*bb*, *cp*, and *lvl*) are present.
trans-unit.target: The *bb* parameter is ignored when all three parameters (*bb*, *cp*, and *lvl*) are present.

trans-unit.source: To control the type of view, use the *ss* (Streetside) and *sty* (style) and parameters.
trans-unit.target: To control the type of view, use the *ss* (Streetside) and *sty* (style) and parameters.

trans-unit.source: The *ss* parameter puts the map into a Streetside view.
trans-unit.target: The *ss* parameter puts the map into a Streetside view.

trans-unit.source: The *sty* parameter lets you switch between road, aerial, and 3D views.
trans-unit.target: The *sty* parameter lets you switch between road, aerial, and 3D views.

trans-unit.source: When using the 3D style, the *hdg*, *pit*, and *rad* parameters can be used to specify the 3D view.
trans-unit.target: When using the 3D style, the *hdg*, *pit*, and *rad* parameters can be used to specify the 3D view.

trans-unit.source: *hdg* specifies the heading of the view, *pit* specifies the pitch of the view, and *rad* specifies the distance from the center point to show in view.
trans-unit.target: *hdg* specifies the heading of the view, *pit* specifies the pitch of the view, and *rad* specifies the distance from the center point to show in view.

trans-unit.source: For more info about these and other parameters, see the [bingmaps: parameter reference](#bingmaps).
trans-unit.target: For more info about these and other parameters, see the [bingmaps: parameter reference](#bingmaps).

trans-unit.source: The **ms-drive-to:** and **ms-walk-to:** URI schemes let you launch directly into a turn-by-turn view of a route.
trans-unit.target: The **ms-drive-to:** and **ms-walk-to:** URI schemes let you launch directly into a turn-by-turn view of a route.

trans-unit.source: These URI schemes can only provide directions from the user's current location.
trans-unit.target: These URI schemes can only provide directions from the user's current location.

trans-unit.source: If you must provide directions between points that do not include the user's current location, use the **binmaps:** URI scheme as described in the previous section.
trans-unit.target: If you must provide directions between points that do not include the user's current location, use the **binmaps:** URI scheme as described in the previous section.

trans-unit.source: **Important** When the **ms-drive-to:** or **ms-walk-to:** URI schemes are launched, the Maps app will check to see if the device has ever had a GPS location fix.
trans-unit.target: **Important** When the **ms-drive-to:** or **ms-walk-to:** URI schemes are launched, the Maps app will check to see if the device has ever had a GPS location fix.

trans-unit.source: If it has, then the Maps app will proceed to turn-by-turn directions.
trans-unit.target: If it has, then the Maps app will proceed to turn-by-turn directions.

trans-unit.source: If it hasn't, the app will display the route overview, as described in [Display directions and traffic](#directions).

trans-unit.target: Each of the waypoints is defined by either a position using latitude and longitude (**cp**) or an address identifier (**where**).

trans-unit.target: A complete route contains exactly two waypoints.
